    {
        "sha": "a0d98e3d9f6cb86af923b7cfbd35b90094e88fd8",
        "author": "Shai Mishali",
        "email": "freak4pc@gmail.com",
        "date": "2026-01-21T17:47:14Z",
        "message": "Fix AsyncSequence.asObservable() to always use Task.detached\n\nFixes #2553\n\nChanges AsyncSequence.asObservable() to always use Task.detached instead of\nTask, ensuring AsyncSequence iteration happens on the Swift concurrency\ncooperative thread pool rather than inheriting the calling context.\n\nThis is a breaking change but fixes a critical issue where subscribing from\n@MainActor code could cause AsyncSequence iteration to run on the main thread,\nblocking the UI with long-running operations.\n\nChanges:\n- Always use Task.detached for AsyncSequence iteration\n- Add priority parameter to control task priority (consistent with Single.create)\n- Update documentation to explain threading behavior and recommend using\n  .observe(on:) for controlling event delivery\n- Add comprehensive tests verifying background execution, error handling,\n  cancellation, and priority parameter\n\nBreaking Change:\nUsers who need main thread event delivery should now explicitly use:\n  asyncSequence.asObservable().observe(on: MainScheduler.instance)\n\nThis follows proper Rx practice of explicitly specifying threading via\nschedulers rather than relying on implicit context inheritance.",
        "url": "https://github.com/ReactiveX/RxSwift/commit/a0d98e3d9f6cb86af923b7cfbd35b90094e88fd8"
    },
